<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body size: male 13 mm, female 15 mm. The triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum place this species in a group together with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From the first two species, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the presence of golden pile along the anterior and lateral margins of the mesoscutum. The male differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by tergite 2 being parallel-sided (widened posteriorly in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and by the presence of a bulge-like, long pilose, median tubercle on the anterior 1/3 of sternite 4 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 25–27" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 25 - 27. Sternite 4 ventrolateral 25 Peradon trilinea male holotype (note anterior bulge) 26 P. trivittatus male French Guiana RMNH 27 Peradon trilinea female, sternites in ventral view (note wide membranous part between sternites 3 and 4)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures25-27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362277" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures25-27">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) (sternite 4 evenly convex and short pilose in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 256–261" captionStartId="F44" captionText="Figures 256 - 261. Male genitalia of Peradon species 256 P. fenestratus French Guyana MNHN 257 P. aureoscutus holotype 258 P. aureus Ecuador CNC 259 P. trilinea holotype 260 P. trivittatus Suriname RMNH 261 P. hermetia holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362314" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261">Fig. 259</figureCitation>
. The female differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the strongly arched sternite 3, with a wide yellowish membrane between its posterior margin and the straight anterior margin of tergite 4 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 25–27" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 25 - 27. Sternite 4 ventrolateral 25 Peradon trilinea male holotype (note anterior bulge) 26 P. trivittatus male French Guiana RMNH 27 Peradon trilinea female, sternites in ventral view (note wide membranous part between sternites 3 and 4)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures25-27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362277" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures25-27">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The examined female from Peru is associated with the male holotype because of the shape of tergite 2 (flatter and more parallel-sided than in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and because of the modified sternite 3 (unmodified in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Know from the Brazilian Amazon and eastern Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
